  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some cultural faux pas when interacting with designers?",
  "response": "Interacting with designers requires an understanding of their creative process and professional culture. Here are some cultural faux pas to avoid when working with designers:\n\n### 1. **Undermining Their Expertise**\n   - **Saying \"It's easy, just do this...\"**: Dismissing their work as simple can feel disrespectful. Design often involves complex problem-solving and skill.\n   - **Ignoring their advice**: Designers are trained professionals; disregarding their input without a constructive reason can be offensive.\n\n### 2. **Micro-Managing Their Creative Process**\n   - **Dictating every detail**: Trust their expertise and allow them creative freedom. Over-control can stifle innovation.\n   - **Demanding endless revisions without clear feedback**: Vague or constantly changing instructions can be frustrating.\n\n### 3. **Valuing Aesthetics Over Functionality**\n   - **Focusing only on \"looking pretty\"**: Design is about solving problems, not just making things visually appealing. Ignoring functionality can miss the purpose of their work.\n\n### 4. **Giving Unconstructive Feedback**\n   - **Saying \"I don\u2019t like it\" without explanation**: Provide specific, actionable feedback to help them improve the design.\n   - **Being overly negative**: Harsh criticism without acknowledging the effort or positive aspects can demoralize them.\n\n### 5. **Ignoring Deadlines or Scope**\n   - **Changing project requirements late in the process**: This can disrupt their workflow and create unnecessary stress.\n   - **Expecting rush work**: Quality design takes time; rushing can compromise the outcome.\n\n### 6. **Not Respecting Intellectual Property**\n   - **Using their work without proper attribution or compensation**: Always credit their work and adhere to agreed terms of use.\n   - **Asking for free work or spec work**: This undervalues their skills and time.\n\n### 7. **Misunderstanding the Role of Design**\n   - **Treating design as an afterthought**: Design should be integral to the project planning, not something tacked on at the end.\n   - **Assuming design is purely subjective**: Design is often based on research, strategy, and user needs, not just personal taste.\n\n### 8. **Pushing Trends Over Purpose**\n   - **Demanding trendy designs without considering relevance**: Trends may not always align with the project\u2019s goals or audience.\n\n### 9. **Interrupting Their Focus**\n   - **Expecting immediate responses**: Designers often need uninterrupted time to concentrate on creative work.\n\n### 10. **Not Respecting Their Time**\n   - **Scheduling unnecessary meetings**: Designers often prefer more time to work rather than attend lengthy discussions.\n   - **Asking for changes outside of agreed-upon hours**: Be mindful of their work-life balance.\n\nBy avoiding these faux pas, you can foster a more productive and respectful relationship with designers, leading to better collaboration and outcomes.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
